President Donald J. Trump has appointed Robert Blair as the Special Representative for International Telecommunications Policy. In this role, Blair will oversee the prioritization of US efforts to promote a secure and reliable global communications system. He will coordinate interagency efforts and act as a liaison to industry, non-governmental, and international stakeholders to support the development, deployment, and operation of next-generation telecommunications infrastructure. Blair will also support the administration's 5G efforts led by Larry Kudlow, the Assistant to the President for Economy Policy. Additionally, Blair will continue to serve as Assistant to the President and Senior Advisor to the Chief of Staff. Prior to joining the White House, Blair held positions at the Office of Management and Budget and the House of Representatives Appropriations Committee. He began his federal service as a Peace Corps Volunteer and holds degrees from Cornell University, Tufts University, and the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy.